              'Grade 4-5': 'Shakespeare presents Macbeth as extremely paranoid in this extract. Macbeth says "every shadow holds a shape" and "every silence hides a voice," which shows he sees threats everywhere even when there are none. He is suspicious of the thanes at the feast and says he will watch their hands to see if they tremble, believing this will reveal who is plotting against him.\n\nMacbeth also refers to himself as "the serpent in the garden" when talking about how he murdered Duncan, comparing himself to the devil. This shows he recognises his own guilt but also fears others might do the same to him. The metaphor of daggers hiding "in cloaks and poison sleeps in wine" shows his paranoia has reached a level where he sees danger in ordinary things like dinner and conversation.\n\nThe fact that he is suspicious even at his own feast shows how isolated he has become. He cannot trust anyone and sees potential betrayal everywhere.',
              'Grade 6-7': 'Shakespeare presents Macbeth\'s paranoia as a psychological consequence of his tyranny, creating a feedback loop where guilt generates suspicion and suspicion generates further violence. The opening lines employ anaphoric repetition — "every shadow," "every silence" — to construct a world in which threat is omnipresent and inescapable, reflecting Macbeth\'s fractured mental state.\n\nThe interrogation of the Servant is revealing: "Do they smile or frown? / Is there a man among them who dares meet / My eye without a flinch?" Macbeth has transformed basic social interaction into an intelligence-gathering exercise. The irony is pointed: he plans to identify his enemies by "the way they hold their cups," yet he himself is the man at the feast whose hands are metaphorically unsteady. This dramatic irony invites the audience to see Macbeth simultaneously as threatening tyrant and terrified man.\n\nThe self-comparison to "the serpent in the garden" is psychologically complex. By identifying himself with the biblical deceiver, Macbeth acknowledges his own capacity for betrayal — and therefore assumes everyone else shares it. His paranoia is, in effect, projection: he trusts no one because he himself is untrustworthy. The closing couplet\'s imagery of "daggers hide in cloaks and poison sleeps in wine" formalises this anxiety through dense, threatening imagery that transforms domestic comfort into mortal danger.\n\nContextually, this reflects Jacobean anxieties about courtly politics and the impossibility of reading true loyalty — relevant to an audience whose king, James I, survived the Gunpowder Plot.',
              'Grade 8-9': 'Shakespeare presents Macbeth\'s paranoia as simultaneously the product and the instrument of tyranny, revealing how political violence corrupts not only its victims but the perpetrator\'s capacity to perceive reality. The extract opens with a remarkable conflation of the sensory and the psychological: "The night is thick with whispers" attributes agency to darkness itself, while "every shadow / Holds a shape that was not there before" suggests that Macbeth\'s guilt has populated the world with phantoms — an externalisation of internal terror that recalls the dagger hallucination and Banquo\'s ghost.\n\nThe rhetorical structure of the Servant interrogation is forensic in its irony. Macbeth\'s conviction that he can read treason in a trembling hand is a grotesque parody of the humanist belief in physiognomy — the idea that outward appearance reveals inner truth. Yet the audience knows that Macbeth\'s own "painted smile" conceals murderous intent, making his surveillance of others a masterclass in dramatic irony. Shakespeare constructs a hall of mirrors: a deceiver seeking to detect deception, a murderer convinced he is surrounded by murderers.\n\nThe self-identification as "the serpent in the garden / That smiled and smiled and struck" is multilayered. The biblical allusion positions regicide as a re-enactment of the Fall, while the repetition of "smiled" — echoing Hamlet\'s "one may smile and smile and be a villain" — emphasises the disjunction between appearance and reality that drives the entire play. Critically, this is not merely confession but explanation: Macbeth understands that his own treachery has made trust impossible, that he has poisoned the very concept of loyalty. The final image — "daggers hide in cloaks and poison sleeps in wine" — transforms the feast, a traditional symbol of community and shared trust, into a theatre of potential assassination. The personification of poison "sleeping" in wine is particularly effective: it suggests latent, patient malice waiting to be activated, mirroring Macbeth\'s own trajectory from loyal thane to hidden killer.\n\nShakespeare uses Macbeth\'s paranoia to explore a profound political insight: that tyranny is inherently unsustainable because it destroys the social trust on which governance depends. A ruler who has seized power through murder can never believe in the loyalty of his subjects, because he has demonstrated that loyalty is a fiction. This self-consuming logic — where power generates the very insecurity it seeks to prevent — makes Macbeth\'s downfall not merely a moral judgement but a structural inevitability.',
